The Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA) said that it would resume the enforcement of the ban on street begging in the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), especially at the city centres. Permanent secretary of FCTA, Sir Chinyeaka Ohaa, who disclosed this at the end of the monthly FCT security committee meeting in Abuja at the weekend, explained that enforcement of the ban became necessary to curtail the likely influx of beggars to the territory following the ban on street begging by some states in the country. Ohaa revealed that relevant officers have been directed to intensify public enlightenment campaigns to reiterate the ban on street begging and to ensure that the FCT does not become a safe haven for beggars. The permanent secretary however, stressed the need for continuous synergy among security agencies for effective performance, just as he attributed the improved security situation in the FCT to the intensified crackdown on criminals by security agencies. He also called on FCT residents to help improve security by always furnishing security operatives with necessary information that would help them in the proper discharge of their duties, adding that the administration would continue to support the security agencies with necessary logistics for their operations. Also speaking, the FCT Commissioner of Police, Bala Ciroma, confirmed that there has been a significant improvement in security situation in the FCT, which he attributed to renewed synergy among security agencies.  